25|$|Until the 1980s, <b>urban</b> <b>water</b> tariffs in China {{were very}} low and sewer tariffs were {{practically}} unknown. This has changed substantially since {{the adoption of}} National Guidelines on <b>Urban</b> <b>Water</b> Tariffs in 1988, which called for increased cost recovery and for the introduction of sewer tariffs. Subsequently, water tariffs have been increased substantially in many Chinese cities, particularly in the north where water is scarcest. However, according to the Ministry of Construction, water tariff reforms have not been effective enough to offer the necessary incentives to save water. While many cities now have sewer tariffs, in 2005, {{there were more than}} 150 cities across the country where no wastewater treatment fee was collected.|$|E
5000|$|The <b>Urban</b> Waste <b>Water</b> Treatment Directive (full title Council Directive 91/271/EEC of 21 May 1991 {{concerning}} urban waste-water treatment) is a European Union directive regarding <b>urban</b> waste <b>water</b> collection, {{waste water}} treatment and its discharge, {{as well as the}} treatment and discharge of [...] "waste water from certain industrial sectors". It was adopted on 21 May 1991. It aims [...] "to protect the environment from the adverse effects of <b>urban</b> waste <b>water</b> discharges and discharges from certain industrial sectors" [...] by mandating waste water collection and treatment in urban agglomerations with a population equivalent of over 2000, and more advanced treatment in places with a population equivalent above 10,000 in sensitive areas.|$|R
